This article is a proclamation by President Barack Obama declaring January 20, 2014, as the Martin Luther King, Jr., Federal Holiday. The article emphasizes the importance of honoring Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.'s contributions to the Civil Rights Movement and his vision of justice and equality for all. It mentions the progress made in the last 50 years, such as civil rights and voting rights laws, but also acknowledges that there is still work to be done. The proclamation encourages Americans to participate in a day of service to build stronger communities and work towards Dr. King's vision.